{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ebaf2342-cc9a-4a24-810d-9ea7a114bbe5","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason message\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason message\")]\n// or for data-driven:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason message\")]\n```\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason message\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason message\")]\n```\n\nAll four will mark the test as \"skipped\" in results (not failed) and display your reason message in the test output.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f21b3a4d-3b74-45e7-b5cd-9dfb384152e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to skip tests with a reason message in MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a straightforward knowledge question about test framework attributes. I can answer this directly without needing to invoke any tools or skills.\n\nHere are the correct attributes:\n\n**MSTest**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n**xUnit**: `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`\n**NUnit**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n**TUnit**: `[Skip(\"reason\")]`\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":296,"requestId":"7C15:1EA0BA:12CA050:153CC4B:69F943A2"},"id":"abab8811-d3b7-454d-922f-7438b9351d4d","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:11:05.461Z","parentId":"b1f87a9a-7478-49a9-a246-085b05b0cf8e"}
